nd literature, Jain explains how a national culture that simultaneously aims to deny, profit from, and cure cancer entraps us in a state of paradox—one that makes the world of cancer virtually impossible to navigate for doctors, patients, caretakers, and policy makers alike. This chronicle, burning with urgency and substance leavened with brio and wit, offers a lucid guide to understanding and navigating the quicksand of uncertainty at the heart of cancer. Malignant vitally shifts the terms of an epic battle we have been losing for decades: the war on cancer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCancerxGovernment policy. 0aCancerxPatients. 0aCancerxResearch. 0aCancerxRisk factorsxGovernment policy. 0aCarcinogensxGovernment policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropological study.  aautobiography.  abiography.  acancer.  acultural analysis.  acultural commentary.  acure cancer.  acure for cancer.  adiagnosis.  adisease.  aeconomics.  aengaging.  afurious debates.  ahealth and medicine.  ahealth policy.  ahealth.  ahuman condition.  aillness and diseases.  aillness.  ainvasive cancer.  alaw.  alife changes.  amedical anthropology.  amedical conditions.  amedical politics.  amedical practice.  amemoir.  anational culture.  aoncology.  apolicy makers.  apublic health.  asocial science.  asocial sciences.  asocial theory.  asociology.  astudy of medicine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027657440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095682740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956827/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Pr